./slot-volatility/index.html:11:<script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What is slot volatility (variance)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Volatility (also called variance) describes how widely a slot’s results swing around its average RTP. Low volatility tends to pay smaller wins more often. High volatility tends to pay less often, but with bigger spikes."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is high volatility better than low volatility?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Neither is better. High volatility fits players who can handle longer dry spells and want a chance at big spikes. Low volatility fits players who want longer sessions and more frequent smaller wins."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can you tell volatility from RTP?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. RTP is the long-run average return. Volatility is the distribution around that average. Two slots can share similar RTP and feel totally different in a real session."}}]}</script>
